statement:
Determine all integers \emph{x} that satisfy the following system of
linear congruences.

\begin{align*}
x &\equiv 3 \mod{6}\\
x &\equiv 1 \mod{10}
\end{align*}

sols:
The conditions

\begin{align*}
x &\equiv 3 \mod{6}\\
x &\equiv 1 \mod{10}
\end{align*}

give us that there is a positive integer \emph{s} such that

\begin{align*}
x &= 3 + 6s.
\end{align*}

Substituting into the second equation yields

\begin{align*}
3 + 6s &\equiv 1 \mod{10}.
\end{align*}

Isolating for 0 gives

\begin{align*}
2(3s +1)&\equiv 0 \mod{10}.
\end{align*}

Hence, we have that 5 must divide the term in the bracket, that is

\begin{align*}
3s+1 \equiv 0 \mod{5}
\end{align*}

This gives

\begin{align*}
3s &\equiv -1 \mod{5}.
\end{align*}

Multiplying both sides by 2 gives

\begin{align*}
s &\equiv -2 \equiv 3 \mod{5}.
\end{align*}

Hence $\displaystyle s = 3 + 5t$ for some integer \emph{t}. Thus,

\begin{align*}
x &= 3 + 6s = 3 + 6(3 + 5t) = 3 + 18 + 30t = 21 + 30t
\end{align*}

and hence all solutions are given by

$\displaystyle x \equiv 21 \mod{30}$.
